 the students' personal struggles with issues such as identity and biculturalism, family dynamics, religion, poverty, stereotypes, and the value of education.Throughout, they provide insights into issues of racial identity in contemporary America among a minority population that is very much in the news. This book gives educators, students, and their families a clear view of the experience of Latino students adapting to a challenging educational environment and a cultural context—Dartmouth College—often very different from their childhood ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHispanic American college studentszNew HampshirezHanovervBiography. 0aHispanic American youthxEducation (Higher)zNew HampshirezHanover. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aLatino/A Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aAcosta, Abiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarez, Alejo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrade, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotto, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrod, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGomez, Christina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKilkenny, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartinez, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeléndez, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRalos, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul